n a pawn and I don't see any way for him to proceed withhis attack.}) 30... Bf5 {Idea: ...Be4. In a chess game, we usually try towithhold information about our intent. Sometimes though, we deliberatelydivulge it to provoke an emotional response from our opponent. In this case,Shabalov unabashedly strives for an assault on g2, with ...Be4, willing togive up material for the right. --- EXERCISE (critical decision): In thiscomplex position, the mind runs unfettered on multiple tracks. Does White havethe time for 31 exd4, or should he play 31 Nf3 - ? One leads to a favourableposition, while the other allows Black's attack to flare.} 31. exd4 $2 {This pawn grab fails to insulate White against Black's coming attack on g2. Hejust doesn't have time for this luxury, and is under no obligation to complywith Black's wishes.} ({ANSWER: White is in control after} 31. Nf3 $1 Rg3 ({or} 31... dxe3 32. Qxe3 Rg3 33. c5 $1 {and White's play looks faster after} Bxh334. cxb6 $1 axb6 35. Bxc6 Bxg2+ 36. Rxg2 Rh3+ 37. Nh2 $1 {; Black's trouble is}Rxe3 {is met by} 38. Rxg8+ Qd8 39. a7 $1 {, winning}) 32. exd4 Be4 33. Ra3 $1Qd7 34. Bxc6 Qxc6 35. Qe2 Qe6 36. Qf1 {. All the threats are covered and it'shard to find a plan to improve Black's position. Black may have somecompensation for the two pawns, but full compensation? I doubt it.}) 31... Be4$1 {The bishop, once bound by a set of strict moral covenants, decides thetime has come to discard them all. Suddenly White is in deep trouble on g2.}32. Rae1 (32. Nf3 $4 {runs into the undermining shot} Rxg2 33. Rxg2 Bxf3 34.Bxc6 Rxg2 35. Bb7+ Kd8 36. Qxg2 Bxg2+ 37. Kxg2 Qxc4 {with a winning position.})32... Rxg2 33. Rxg2 Rxg2 34. Qxg2 ({White has no choice but to hand over thequeen, since} 34. Rxe4 $4 {walks into} Qxh2# {.}) 34... Bxg2+ 35. Kxg2 {White has a rook, bishop and pawn for the queen, but his position probablycan't be held, for two reasons: -- 1. Black's queen will seek out and findmultiple vulnerable pawn targets. 