 KID position. --- QUESTION: What about the fact that Whitecan win the bishop pair? --- ANSWER: I'm not sure the bishop pair is such agreat prize in this position, since it's Black's bad bishop, and the game fornow is closed, so Black's knights easily hold their own.} 12. a4 $6 {I don'tlike this move, which renders White's play starchy and stiff.} ({He shouldtake immediate action with} 12. c3 b5 13. Nxd6 Qxd6 14. cxd4 cxd4 15. Nh4 Rac816. Rf1 {(as mentioned in a note above, White's rook is misplaced on e1 whenthe game turns into a reversed KID)} Nb4 $1 17. f4 ({if} 17. a3 Nc2 {and Whitemust give up his a-pawn, since} 18. Ra2 $2 {is met strongly by} Be6) 17... f618. fxe5 fxe5 19. Rxf8+ Rxf8 20. a3 Nbc6 {. The players agreed to a draw inthis approximately even position, B.Khatanbaatar-J.Sequera Paolini, BledOlympiad 2002.}) 12... b6 13. Qd2 {We arrive at theory's end around here.Black achieved an excellent reversed KID position for the following reasons:-- 1. White's b2-bishop is obviously misplaced, since it stares at a wall ond4. -- 2. White's rook belongs on f1, rather than e1. -- 3. Black has accessto quick queenside play with ...a6 and ...b5. -- 4. In some cases, as in thisgame, Black can go for a direct attack on White's king with an ...f5 break.} ({Instead,} 13. Nh4 a6 14. Qh5 b5 (14... f6 $1 15. Nf5 g6 16. Nh6+ Kg7 17. Qh4Nb4 18. Re2 b5 19. Nxd6 Qxd6 {favours Black, since the opening of the a-fileleads to infiltration, while} 20. a5 {dooms the artificially isolated a-pawn,eventually}) 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. Nf5 Nxf5 17. exf5 bxa4 18. Rxa4 Nb4 19. Bxa8 $6({White should be okay after the correct} 19. Ra5 $1 Bc6 20. Re2 f6) 19... Bxa4{was M.Tonnicchi-D.Schmidt, correspondence 1999. My database has Whiteresigning here, though the position is still close to even after} 20. Be4 Nxc221. bxa4 $1 Nxe1 22. Ba3 {, when Qe2 is coming and the knight is trapped. Thegame is unclear after} Nxd3 23. Bxd3 Rb8 24. Qf3 {.}) 13... f6 14. h4 $5 {This ambitious move is questionable, since it weakens White's king. However,it does prevent ...g5 and also worries Black about future ideas like Kh2 andBh3.} Qb8 {Sigh. Mednis gives this move and Karpov's next three moves exclams.In the 80s I was a book reviewer (and a very kindly one - not like some of themean-spirited buggers who infest the chess world today!), and as I recall, aMednis book was the only one which I reviewed slightly unfavourably, since heshowered his favourite sons with undeserved exclams! I'm not so sure this moveis so great. The idea is to provoke Nxd6.} ({Alternatives: -- a)} 14... a6 15.a5 $1 Nxa5 ({not} 15... b5 $6 16. Nb6 Rab8 17. Nxd7 {, swapping away Black'sbest minor piece}) 16. Nxa5 bxa5 17. Rxa5 Nc6 18. Raa1 a5 {, intending to pryopen the queenside with an eventual ...a4.}) ({b)} 14... h6 $6 {(the beginningof an incorrect plan)} 15. Kh2 g5 $5 {. This move halts the intended Bh3, butWhite can now sac with} 16. hxg5 hxg5 17. Nxg5 $1 fxg5 18. Qxg5+ Kf7 19. Bf3Ke8 20. Qh6 {(threatening d6)} Nc8 21. Bh5+ Kd8 22. Bc1 $1 Qb8 23. Bg5+ Kc7 24.f4 {, when I think White's attack and two pawns are worth more than Black'sextra piece.}) 15. Ba3 $6 {A violation of the principle: The cramped sideshould seek exchanges.} ({I think he should take the bad bishop and hope toopen the position later on, with} 15. Nxd6 {.}) 15... Bc7 {Following theconverse of the above principle.} 16. Reb1 {I think this may be anotherviolation of principle: Don't play on the opponent's strong wing. Black has aspace advantage on the queenside.} ({Therefore White should think aboutsomething like} 16. h5 a6 {(threat: ...b5 and ...b4, winning a piece)} 17. Qe2Bg4 18. h6 g6 19. Kh2 b5 20. Ncd2 {, although Black stands clearly better hereas well.}) 16... Be6 17. Kh2 {Intending Bh3, which Black prevents.} Qc8 18. Qe2$6 {A waste of time. Nobody can claim this game represents a clash ofelemental passions. White is trying to out-Karpov Karpov, which isn't so easyto do.} ({Maybe White should go into desperation mode and strike out with theanti-positional} 18. b4 $5 cxb4 19. Bxb4 Nxb4 20. Qxb4 Nc6 21. Qb5 {with aninferior position, but also some possibility of play on the queenside.}) 18...Bg4 $1 {Intending ...f5.} 19. Qf1 $6 {If we are going to worry and expendtremendous amounts of energy on a project, then make certain it is somethingworthwhile. This pretzel-like move, keeping the queen on the soon-to-openf-file, basically tells the opponent: "Here I am. Come and get me. "} ({White should just admit his last move wasn't so great, and get out of the pinand off the f-file with} 19. Qd2 {.}) 19... f5 {One sec. Let me check ifMednis gave this completely natural move an exclam... Hi, I'm back. Yes, hedid give it an exclam. Petrosian once wrote that he often experiencedhesitation taking action when in a superior position, since he wanted toprolong his edge ad infinitum, without altering the landscape and riskingchange. I consider Karpov kind of a super-Petrosian, who not only hadPetrosian's strategic power of bleeding the opponent's position dry ofdynamism, but also proactively took action when needed.} 20. Ncd2 (20. exf5 {hangs a pawn to} Qxf5 21. Ng5 Qxf2 {.}) 20... f4 $1 {Karpov goes forstrangulation.} 21. Bh3 h5 $1 {Now White can't afford to swap away his badbishop.} 22. Qg2 Ng6 {Pieces continue to congregate around White's king.} 23.Ng5 {This move just loses time. I think White has to try something, anything,or he risks slow death on the kingside.} ({I would once again try} 23. b4 {.})23... Bd8 24. Ngf3 ({After} 24. Ndf3 Nb4 25. Rb2 Qd7 {, Black can slowlyprepare to double rooks on the f-file.}) 24... Be7 {Clamping down on b4desperadoes.} 25. Rg1 Qe6 26. Raf1 Rf7 27. Rh1 Raf8 28. Kg1 Qd6 29. Kh2 a6 $1 {Principle: When you tie an opponent down on one side, open up a second front,where the unprepared defenders experience difficulty coordinating.} 30. Kg1 Rf631. Bxg4 $5 {Gulp! Don't toss a bucket of chum into the oc