d me earlier in the game!), and now seek redress. White's overextendedposition reminds us of Babylon and ancient Rome, whose decadence induced theirfall.} 30. Qa8+ Bg8 {I didn't want to swap queens, since his king is by farthe more exposed of the two.} 31. Qc8 $2 {EXERCISE (combination alert): Thisis a place where outlaws may easily prey on the unsuspecting traveller.White's last move was an error in a difficult position. How can Black exploitit?} h6 $6 {The most gratifying part of living with low expectations is thefact that I factor in my own errors, so that I am not so disappointed when Icommit them.} ({ANSWER: I missed the idea of pinning:} 31... Qg4 $1 {, whenWhite is curiously helpless against the threat of ...Bf4! followed by ...Qf3+and ...Be3 mate. For example:} 32. Qc2 (32. a3 {and the do-nothing plan is metby} Bf4 $1 33. d5 Qf3+ 34. Kg1 Be3# {.}) (32. Rf8 Qe4+ 33. Kg1 Qxd4+ 34. Kf1Bxf8 {wins.} (34... --)) 32... Be6 33. Rg5 Qxh4 34. Qg2 Bxh2 $1 {also wins.})32. h5 $2 {He forces me into the winning idea.} (32. Rf2 {holds out longer.})32... Qg4 $1 {I twirled my moustache evilly, in silent movie-villain fashionas I made this move. The effect, I readily admit, was a bit weakened by thefact that I didn't have a moustache. Now I see the winning geometry, where thetoxicity of his weak light squares slowly poisons his king. There is no goodanswer to the threat of ...Bf4, ...Qf3+ and ...Be3 mate.} 33. Rf8 Qe4+ 34. Kg1Qxd4+ 35. Kf1 Bxf8 36. Qxf8 Qg7 {. --- SUMMARY: White's 8 Nh4 plan is nolonger considered dangerous for Black, who has multiple equalizing responses.}0-1[Event "Groningen"][Site "?"][Date "1997.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Maiwald, J."][Black "Gurevich, M."][Result "0-1"][ECO "C00"][Annotator "Cyrus Lakdawala"][PlyCount "70"][EventDate "1997.??.??"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2016.03.01"]1. e4 e6 {We can also reach our position via a French move order.} (1... c5 2.Nf3 e6 3. Qe2 Nc6 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O 