ce, since he has no prayer against Black's connectedkingside passers.} 40. Rd7 g6 41. Rxa6 Kg5 42. b3 Bg3 {. The h-pawn is toofast. --- SUMMARY: I like the 6...Nge7 line against the Smith-Morra Gambit,where we develop our pieces in Kan Sicilian fashion.} 0-1[Event "Mainz (rapid)"][Site "?"][Date "2010.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Chladek, V."][Black "Gashimov, V."][Result "0-1"][ECO "B21"][Annotator "Cyrus Lakdawala"][PlyCount "52"][EventDate "2010.??.??"][EventType "rapid"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2016.03.01"]1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 dxc3 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Bc4 Nge7 7. O-O {In this game we look at positions where White declines to toss in Bg5 andprovoke Black into a concession with ...f6. QUESTION: Which version is betterfor Black? --- ANSWER: I think Black benefits when White fails to play Bg5,since ...f6 loosens our pawn front and weakens e6. In this game's version,Black's position looks more solid; and so, logically, White's compensation isless as well.} Ng6 (7... a6 {is more commonly played, and normally transposesto positions we reach later on.}) 8. Qe2 ({Alternatively: -- a)} 8. Be3 Be7 {(I would prevent Bg5 as quickly as possible)} 9. Rc1 O-O 10. a3 a6 11. b4 b512. Ba2 Bb7 13. Qe2 Rc8 14. Rfd1 Nce5 {(intending to occupy c4)} 15. Nd2 $6 {(White loses the initiative after this passive move)} ({he should think aboutthe bailout line} 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Bd4 Nc4 17. a4 e5 18. Bc5 Bxc5 19. bxc5Rxc5 20. axb5 axb5 21. Nxb5 Rxb5 22. Bxc4 Rb6 {, when Black is up a pawn, butconversion is a long way off}) 15... Bg5 $1 {(seizing control over f4)} 16. Nb3{, B.Berg-L.Degerman, Stockholm 1994. Black has an extra pawn and astrategically won game after} Nf4 17. Bxf4 Bxf4 18. Rc2 Qh4 $1 19. h3 d6 {.}) ({b) As the old saying goes: Better late than never. I think} 8. Bg5 {is stillWhite's best move.} f6 ({QUESTION: Can't Black gain time with} 8... Be7 {- ? --- ANSWER: Black gains time at the cost of weakening d6 after} 9. Bxe7